         <abstract>
            <p>This paper measures the ability of managers to time the flotation of shelf-registered bonds so it occurs at low points in the interest rate cycle. The timing performance of managers is then measured against the performance achieved by a naive strategy for selecting issue dates. During the period of March 1982 to June 1985, managers were able to achieve on average an 8.1 basis point lower yield than the naive strategy of selecting an issue date at random. This level of timing performance by managers exceeded that achieved by the naive strategy at better than the 95% level of statistical significance. A breakdown of performance by industry revealed that nonbank issuers were superior to bank and finance issuers in timing performance.</p>
         </abstract>
